Karomia speciosa is an African deciduous large shrub or bushy tree up to 7 m, and relocated to the family Lamiaceae from Verbenaceae. It is one of 9 species in the genus Karomia, a genus containing species previously classified in Holmskioldia, and is closely related to Clerodendrum. The only remaining species in the genus is Holmskioldia sanguinea, occurring in the foothills of the Himalayas." "d9430b96-b8cd-442e-8276-98d32d32ebe8"	"d9430b96-b8cd-442e-8276-98d32d32ebe8"	"Trilepisium gymnandrum (Baker) J.Gerlach"	""	"Plantae"	"Tracheophyta"	"Asteropsida"	"Rosales"	"Moraceae"	"Trilepisium"	"gymnandrum"	""	""	"Bosquéa, Bouskiya"	"ACCEPTED"	""	"Described as a Seychelles endemic Bosqueia gymnandra Baker 1877 but referred to Trilepisium madagascariense by Berg 1977. Subsequently gymnandra resurrected as T. gymnandrum (Gerlach 2000) on the basis of floristic differences between Seychelles and Afro-Malagasy specimens. Only five mature individuals are known on a single island of 1,995 ha. This qualifies for Critically Endangered on the basis of the number of mature individuals. Has a very restricted range, but as there is no continuing decline, does not qualify for any of the other criteria." It is for sure not a Leea guineensis (which was describe based on a Mauritian specimen). Today I just received a specimen from someone in Mauritius that has a plant that seems the same of your photo. It does not fit the description of L rubra fully, I will need more time to check which other species could be. Leea conccinea is today a synonym of L guineensis. I'm not sure if we will be able to restate the name because until now, we cannot relocate the sample used for the description of the species, and Bojer's account does not allow us to match a species now. Anyway, L concinnea, even if we can use the name, it would be probably a Mauritian endemic. In January I sent to Mayotte for a workshop on invasive species and I saw one of their Leea that is being called L guineensis. For sure it is not the same as in Mauritius. Best; See also publication by Molina et al (2013)"	""	10	"Dicotyledon"	"Seed plants"	"Vascular plants"		0	0	1	0	"ar|shrubs|ar|Strates inférieures (understorey) [Inf]"	"Garden"	"Leea coccinea "	"adult"	"present"	"introduced"	"casual"	""	8001294		"Leea coccinea Planch." "3c55188f-7247-4a9a-9fcd-569bc688b2dc"	"3c55188f-7247-4a9a-9fcd-569bc688b2dc"	"Anthurium andraeanum Linden ex André"	""	"Plantae"	"Tracheophyta"	"Liliopsida"	"Alismatales"	"Araceae"	"Anthurium"	"andraeanum"	""	""	"Antiryonm"	"ACCEPTED"	""	"Checked in the Plant List." "175f9c3c-0125-4faf-8972-d62c68e9ffe1"	"175f9c3c-0125-4faf-8972-d62c68e9ffe1"	"Anthurium crystallinum Linden & André"	""	"Plantae"	"Tracheophyta"	"Liliopsida"	"Alismatales"	"Araceae"	"Anthurium"	"crystallinum"	""	""	"Antiryonm"	"ACCEPTED"	""	"Anthurium crystallinum is a member of section Cardiolonchium and the leaf blades of accepted specimens are sub-coriaceous (just less than leathery).  They possess an attractive yet dark green coloration with a velutinous (velvety) appearance on the adaxial (upper) portion of the leaf blade.  The leaf veins are pale green along the major veins with the abaxial (lower) surface a much paler green than the top of the blade.  New leaf blades as well as the undersides of the adult leaf and petiole are sometimes tinged red-violet.  Blades normally measure 25 to 39 cm long (10 to 11 1/2 inches.  The largest leaf of our three specimens currently measures (December, 2006) 31cm (12 1/4 inches.  The Anthurium produces a reddish tinged spathe with a yellow spadix.  The spadix has a very faint yet pleasant aroma once the stamens emerge...A. crystallinum is most closely related to Anthurium papillilaminum but bears some resemblance to A. clarinervium, thus the common confusion between the two species.  I have even seen a few photos of Anthurium crystallinum noted as being Anthurium regale which is from Peru.  Again, there is a resemblance, but Anthurium regale grows substantially larger and is even more beautiful.  Anthurium crystallinum requires high humidity and grows well in a hanging basket provided the soil mixture is extremely fast draining.  We use a mixture of good moisture control soil, peat, orchid potting media and Perlite™.  The soil mixture should not be allowed to completely dry." "2d19c836-bae7-4ae0-bb5c-411479dec55e"	"2d19c836-bae7-4ae0-bb5c-411479dec55e"	"Tabebuia heterophylla (DC.) Britton"	""	"Plantae"	"Tracheophyta"	"Asteropsida"	"Lamiales"	"Bignoniaceae"	"Tabebuia"	"heterophylla"	""	""	"Calice du pape, Kalis di pap, Kalisdipap, Tecoma, White cedar"	"ACCEPTED"	""	"This is generally known in Seychelles as Tabebuia pallida, which is not consensually synonyme of T. heterophylla. I refer mostly to the detailed discussion of Gentry (http://www.sci.sdsu.edu/plants/chile/pdfs/Gentry1992-Bignoniac.pdf), who kept the two names as distinct species. According to Gentry, T. pallida has uni-foliolate leaves, and the 3-5-foliolate form corresponds to T. heterophylla subsp. pallida sensu Stehle (1946) which he considers distinct from true T. pallida and conspecific to T. heterophylla. Therefore, T. pallida would be a missapplied name in Seychelles, where it has been confused with T. heterophylla." "544bb465-c4ec-4f82-987d-604da00e60b9"	"544bb465-c4ec-4f82-987d-604da00e60b9"	"Mapania angustifolia (C.B.Clarke) Senterre unpublished"	"This current dataset"	"Plantae"	"Tracheophyta"	"Liliopsida"	"Poales"	"Cyperaceae"	"Mapania"	"angustifolia"	""	""	""	"ACCEPTED"	""	"Synonymie confuse dans la biblio: synof. M. floribundum pour Robertson, mais correspondant à la petite espèce dans Beaver (2000) laquelle est nommée T. seychellaria par Wize. En fait, M. seychellaria est une espèce à part, de Praslin, décrite en 1992. A Mahé, trois épithètes on été décrits: floribundum en 1857, puis seychellense et angustifolium en 1908 (sans commentaire sur le nom floribundum qu'on croyait de Madagascar?). D'après Simpson (1992), floribundum est = à seychellense; Il considère également angustifolium comme identique mais ayant des feuilles plus étroites, une taille plus petite et des inflorescences moins grandes, à moins d'épillets. Ces deux formes semblent se reconnaître à Mahé, et je préfère suivre Clarke et Uittien, et donc distinguer 3 taxa en tout ... (?)" "Kafe maron-d-rivyer, Kafemarondrivyer"	"ACCEPTED"	""	"Not seen on Mahé for more than a century. Rare on Silhouette. Note (Senterre 2016): A recent revision (Davis & Bridson 2004) considered that the Seychelles plants are the same as the type subspecies from Java; nevertheless, they focussed on leaf characters and neglected floral and fruiting characters; the diagnostic characters given by Friedmann are strong and I think that not only the Seychelles plant diserves its endemic status but even a species rather than subspecies status; the Friedmann's name 'sechellarum' was supperfluous since Baker had already named the Seychelles plants 'ferruginea'; The name to be published would thus be 'Amaracarpus ferrugine-us-a?'." Angraecun eburneum ssp typicum est une grosse orchidée que l'on trouve entre 100 et 800 mètres d'altitude, avec de 1 à 5 hampes par plante, les fleurs bicolores 4-16 par hampe font 5 à 8 cm de diamètre avec un éperon de 7-11 cm de long, la variabilité de la plante et de la fleur est très fréquente suivant le site, zones humide ou zones sèche." "b2ad3b27-9789-4e24-b280-eb80153a8c62"	"b2ad3b27-9789-4e24-b280-eb80153a8c62"	"Selaginella sechellarum Baker"	""	"Plantae"	"Tracheophyta"	"Lycopodiopsida"	"Selaginellales"	"Selaginellaceae"	"Selaginella"	"sechellarum"	""	""	"Lapat lezar"	"ACCEPTED"	""	"General habit very like that of S. kraussiana, but the stem not articulated (Baker 1877: 523); -S. sechellarum: leaves at the ends slightly overlapping (edge to edge in S. fissidentoides var. amphirrhizos); leaves slightly dentate throughout (not or only at base for S. fissidentoides var. amphirrhizos); leaves  membranous (moderately firm in texture in S. amphirrhizos); bracts lanceolate (deltoid in S. amphirrhizos). The species present in Seychelles is doubtfully distinct from S. fissidentoides. If they are conspecific, then S. fissidentoides occurs in Seychelles; if not then Baker's S. fissidentoides has most probably been confused with S. sechellarum and does not actually occur (although both species could also be present)."
